To gain insight into the fluorescence-enhancing mechanism further, TCSPC analysis was carried out for BS-CDs in the presence and absence of FA (Fig. 4
                        ). The fluorescence lifetime profile for free BS-CDs was found to be 4.08 ns and best fitted with a bi-exponential function (Table 1
                        ). After the addition of 5 → 7 → 10 → 15 μL of FA to the BS-CDs solution, the fluorescence lifetime value was slightly increased (4.42 → 4.43 → 4.47 → 4.67 ns, respectively) without changing bi-functionality. This biexponential decay data confirms the presence of two distinct species such as free and FA-bound forms of BS-CDs in the solution. The time-resolved fluorescence results imply that there is no significant change in the decay time of BS-CDs at the maximum concentration of FA (15 μL) due to the formation of a ground state complex between BS-CDs and FA [62].

The newly developed fluorescence probe (BS-CDs) was utilized for detecting FA in urine samples. Following the standard addition method, a known concentration of FA (5.3 μ M) was spiked into the human urine sample. Then, FA-spiked human urine samples were added to the BS-CDs solution (100 μM), and emission intensity was monitored (Fig. 7
                        ). As illustrated in Fig. 7, the emission spectra of BS-CDs were enhanced upon the insertion of bare FA, and FA spiked urine samples (U1-U4). Based on the attained corresponding fluorescence intensity, the recovery percentages of FA in urine samples were calculated and found to be between 103 and 109 %, respectively, with a relative standard deviation (RSD) of <1.5 % (Table 2
                        ). The current method shows excellent accuracy and recovery and its potential to perform FA detection in real samples. Furthermore, this method is easy to handle, a rapid, inexpensive, sensitive, and selective tool for FA detection in biological fluids [83,84].
